      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely! The circle of fifths works the same way for flats as it does for sharps, just in the opposite direction.  \nThink of it as a double‑track: clockwise is the “sharp track” and counter‑clockwise is the “flat track.”  \nSo if you see a key signature with flats, you’ll look at the bottom half of the circle and move counter‑clockwise.\n\n**How to use it for flats**  \n- **Start at the top again** – C major has no flats.  \n- **Move counter‑clockwise** – each step down a fifth adds one flat.  \n  - C → F → B♭ → E♭ → A♭ → D♭  \n  - The first flat is in F major, the second in B♭ major, the third in E♭ major, and so on.  \n- **Count the flats** – if you see two flats in the key signature, that’s B♭ major (or its relative minor, D♭ minor).  \n  - The flats will be B♭ and E♭.  \n  - On the circle, that’s the second step counter‑clockwise from C.\n\n**",
